<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-374-982  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 374 982.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  May 1989 v40 n5 p20(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Implementing case tools. (computer-aided software engineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burkhard, Donald L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The implementation of computer aided software engineering (CASE)technology can be more effective certain guidelines are followed.andO;A commitment to structured techniques in systems development isessential.andP;  A structured methodology, if not currently in use, canbe implemented concurrently with CASE or prior to it.andP;  The best,most productive users should be the group assigned to a pilot CASEproject.andP;  The project should be a reasonably sized, non-criticalone that would take less than a year to complete without CASE.andO;CASE can be justified on the basis of increased productivity anddecreased software maintenance.andP;  It is important to remember,though, that reduction in maintenance occurs only on theCASE-built systems.andP;  Significant reductions in maintenance onexisting systems will only occur if the system is retired andre-engineered by CASE tools.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-aided software engineeringAutomationSystem DevelopmentImplementationGuidelines.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Components of the CASE tool set. (chart)Type of CASE tools for various life cycle phases. (chart)Shifting the productivity curve. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>